SENATE RESOLUTION 390
By Walley
A RESOLUTION to commend Sergeant Cody Cloud and Deputy
Kyle Cupples of the Chester County Sheriff's
Office.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this legislative body should salute those first
responders who, in the course of discharging their vital public duties, provide services that
dramatically improve outcomes for individuals in peril; and
WHEREAS, Sergeant Cody Cloud and Deputy Kyle Cupples of the Chester County
Sheriff's Office were recently recognized as being the top submitters of Handle With Care
notifications in 2025; and
WHEREAS, Handle with Care is a program that enables first responders, including law
enforcement, fire, or EMS individuals, to notify schools if they encounter a child at a traumatic
scene, so that schools and mental healthcare leaders can provide trauma-sensitive support right
away; and
WHEREAS, the statewide Handle with Care program is coordinated by the Tennessee
Bureau of Investigation's Dangerous Drugs Taskforce through a State grant; technical
assistance, training, and program support are provided at no cost to the county; the program
has been active in Chester County since 2022; and
WHEREAS, Sergeant Cody Cloud and Deputy Kyle Cupples have worked diligently to
safeguard the well-being of children throughout Chester County; and
WHEREAS, these exemplary professionals are truly dedicated to protecting the youth of
Tennessee, and they should be recognized for their prodigious efforts; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we commend Sergeant Cody
Cloud and Deputy Kyle Cupples of the Chester County Sheriff's Office for being the top
